        </div>
        <div class="col-lg-5 h-100 jm-sticky-top mr-auto order-2 order-lg-1">
            @*<h3>What is a composting tumbler?</h3>*@
            <p class="mb-4" style="color:black;">
                4. Harvest your finished compost. Over time, the material at the bottom of your pile (or bin) will start to look like the nicest, richest soil you’ve ever seen. When you don’t see any more recognizable scraps, the compost is ready to be used.<br />
                5. Harvest your compost from the bottom of your pile (or bin) once or twice a year. Whatever isn’t yet ready just goes back into the pile to continue breaking down.<br />
                6. Spread your finished compost on your garden beds or use it in container gardens.<br />
                <strong>Note</strong>: You probably don’t want to bring your fresh compost into the house since it should be home to many, many little critters.
            </p>
